From Queries to Business Decisions

This project goes beyond writing SQL queries. It focuses on how data answers real business questions. Each query represents a decision point for marketing, sales, or operations.

I approached this like a data analyst. Not just pulling numbers, but asking what the numbers mean.

Customer Diversity Analysis
I started by checking how global the business is.

SQL used:
SELECT DISTINCT Country AS customer_country FROM Customers;

What I saw:
Customers are spread across many countries.

What it means:
The business is not local. It operates globally.

Decision angle:
Marketing should not treat all customers the same. Campaigns should be region-specific. Expansion strategy should focus on already strong regions.

Missing Data Audit
Next, I checked data quality.

SQL used:
SELECT CustomerID, CompanyName, Country
FROM Customers
WHERE Region IS NULL;

What I saw:
Some customers have no region assigned.

What it means:
There is incomplete data.

Decision angle:
This affects logistics and targeting. The business should enforce required fields during data entry. Clean data leads to better decisions.

Order Volume Overview
I wanted a quick snapshot of activity.

SQL used:
SELECT COUNT(*) AS total_orders FROM Orders;

What I saw:
Total number of orders placed.

What it means:
This shows how active the business is.

Decision angle:
Useful for tracking growth over time. Management can compare this monthly or yearly.

Revenue Calculation
Now I moved to money.

SQL used:
SELECT SUM(UnitPrice * Quantity * (1 - Discount)) AS total_revenue
FROM "Order Details";

What I saw:
Total revenue generated.

What it means:
This is the actual value the business is making.

Decision angle:
Helps track performance. Can guide pricing, discount strategy, and sales targets.

Product Performance by Category
I checked how products are distributed.

SQL used:
SELECT CategoryID, COUNT(ProductID) AS product_count
FROM Products
GROUP BY CategoryID;

What I saw:
Some categories have more products than others.

What it means:
Product offering is uneven.

Decision angle:
The business can expand underrepresented categories or double down on strong ones.

High Value Customers
I looked for customers driving activity.

SQL used:
SELECT CustomerID, COUNT() AS order_count
FROM Orders
GROUP BY CustomerID
HAVING COUNT() > 10;

What I saw:
A small group of customers place many orders.

What it means:
Revenue is concentrated.

Decision angle:
These customers should be prioritized. Loyalty programs, direct engagement, and retention strategies should focus here.

Average Freight by Customer
I explored cost behavior.

SQL used:
SELECT CustomerID, AVG(Freight) AS avg_freight
FROM Orders
GROUP BY CustomerID;

What I saw:
Freight costs vary across customers.

What it means:
Shipping cost is inconsistent.

Decision angle:
The business can optimize logistics. High freight customers may need better routing or pricing adjustments.

Suppliers with Multiple Products
I checked supplier strength.

SQL used:
SELECT SupplierID, COUNT(ProductID) AS product_supply_count
FROM Products
GROUP BY SupplierID
HAVING COUNT(ProductID) > 5;

What I saw:
Few suppliers supply multiple products.

What it means:
Supplier base is spread out.

Decision angle:
The company can evaluate if consolidation improves efficiency or if diversification reduces risk.

Countries with High Customer Base
I identified strong markets.

SQL used:
SELECT Country, COUNT(CustomerID) AS customer_count
FROM Customers
GROUP BY Country
HAVING COUNT(CustomerID) > 5;

What I saw:
Some countries have many customers.

What it means:
These are core markets.

Decision angle:
Focus marketing spend here. Expand operations where demand already exists.

Orders Without Shipment
Finally, I checked operations.

SQL used:
SELECT COUNT(*) AS pending_shipments
FROM Orders
WHERE ShippedDate IS NULL;

What I saw:
Some orders are not shipped.

What it means:
There are delays.

Decision angle:
Operations team needs to investigate. Delays affect customer satisfaction and revenue flow.

Final Reflection

This project shows how SQL moves from syntax to impact.

You:
Ask the right questions
Query the data
Interpret the output
Turn it into decisions

That is the real job.

SQL gives you answers.
Analysis gives those answers meaning.
